WEBVTT

00:24.760 --> 00:28.520
CHAPTER XI. SERIOUS READING

00:30.760 --> 00:37.080
Novels are excluded from serious reading, so that the man who, bent on self-improvement,

00:37.480 --> 00:42.220
has been deciding to devote ninety minutes three times a week to a complete study of

00:42.220 --> 00:46.780
the works of Charles Dickens would be well advised to alter his plans.

00:47.880 --> 00:50.980
The reason is not that novels are not serious.

00:51.640 --> 00:55.180
Some of the great literature of the world is in the form of prose fiction.

00:55.820 --> 01:02.100
The reason is that bad novels ought not to be read, and that good novels never demand

01:02.100 --> 01:05.440
any appreciable mental application on the part of the reader.

01:06.340 --> 01:10.120
It is only the bad parts of Meredith's novels that are difficult.

01:10.960 --> 01:16.240
A good novel rushes you forward like a skiff down a stream, and you arrive at the end,

01:16.520 --> 01:19.240
perhaps breathless, but unexhausted.

01:20.120 --> 01:23.320
The best novels involve the least strain.

01:24.100 --> 01:29.960
Now, in the cultivation of the mind, one of the most important factors is precisely the

01:29.960 --> 01:36.400
feeling of strain, of difficulty, of a task which one part of you is anxious to achieve,

01:36.860 --> 01:39.400
and another part of you is anxious to shirk.

01:39.900 --> 01:43.000
And that feeling cannot be got in facing a novel.

01:43.700 --> 01:47.940
You do not set your teeth in order to read Anna Karenina.

01:48.800 --> 01:54.380
Therefore, though you should read novels, you should not read them in those ninety minutes.

01:55.900 --> 01:59.920
Imaginative poetry produces a far greater mental strain than novels.

02:00.420 --> 02:04.160
It produces probably the severest strain of any form of literature.

02:04.980 --> 02:07.300
It is the highest form of literature.

02:08.000 --> 02:12.900
It yields the highest form of pleasure, and teaches the highest form of wisdom.

02:13.700 --> 02:17.220
In a word, there is nothing to compare with it.

02:17.220 --> 02:23.880
I say this with sad consciousness of the fact that the majority of people do not read poetry.

02:24.340 --> 02:29.420
I am persuaded that many excellent persons, if they were confronted with the alternatives

02:29.420 --> 02:35.560
of reading Paradise Lost, and going round Trafalgar Square at noonday on their knees

02:35.560 --> 02:39.920
in sackcloth, would choose the ordeal of public ridicule.

02:40.680 --> 02:47.480
Still, I will never cease advising my friends and enemies to read poetry before anything.

02:48.580 --> 02:55.500
If poetry is what is called a sealed book to you, begin by reading Haslett's famous essay on the

02:55.500 --> 03:01.980
nature of poetry in general. It is the best thing of its kind in English, and no one who has read

03:01.980 --> 03:09.020
it can possibly be under the misapprehension that poetry is a medieval torture, or a mad elephant,

03:09.020 --> 03:16.280
or a gun that will go off by itself and kill it forty paces. Indeed, it is difficult to imagine

03:16.280 --> 03:22.720
the mental state of the man who, after reading Haslett's essay, is not urgently desirous of

03:22.720 --> 03:29.840
reading some poetry before his next meal. If the essay so inspires you, I would suggest that you

03:29.840 --> 03:37.040
make a commencement with purely narrative poetry. There is an infinitely finer English novel,

03:37.040 --> 03:43.440
written by a woman, than anything by George Eliot or the Brontes, or even Jane Austen,

03:43.660 --> 03:51.620
which perhaps you have not read. Its title is Aurora Lee, and its author E. B. Browning.

03:52.160 --> 03:57.900
It happens to be written in verse, and to contain a considerable amount of genuinely fine poetry.

03:58.840 --> 04:05.420
Decide to read that book through, even if you die for it. Forget that it is fine poetry,

04:05.420 --> 04:12.740
read it simply for the story and the social ideas, and when you have done, ask yourself honestly

04:12.740 --> 04:20.280
whether you still dislike poetry. I have known more than one person to whom Aurora Lee has been

04:20.280 --> 04:26.020
the means of proving that, in assuming they hated poetry, they were entirely mistaken.

04:27.120 --> 04:33.000
Of course, if, after Haslett, and such an experiment made in the light of Haslett,

04:33.000 --> 04:38.500
you are finally assured that there is something in you which is antagonistic to poetry,

04:39.100 --> 04:45.820
you must be content with history or philosophy. I shall regret it, yet not inconsolably.

04:46.540 --> 04:53.100
The decline in fall is not to be named in the same day with Paradise Lost, but it is a vastly

04:53.100 --> 04:59.160
pretty thing, and Herbert Spencer's First Principles simply laughs at the claims of

04:59.160 --> 05:04.940
poetry, and refuses to be accepted as ought but the most majestic product of any human mind.

05:05.820 --> 05:11.200
I do not suggest that either of these works is suitable for a tyro in mental strains,

05:11.840 --> 05:18.340
but I see no reason why any man of average intelligence should not, after a year of

05:18.340 --> 05:25.180
continuous reading, be fit to assault the supreme masterpieces of history or philosophy.

05:25.980 --> 05:32.000
The great convenience of masterpieces is that they are so astonishingly lucid.

05:33.100 --> 05:39.820
I suggest no particular work as a start. The attempt would be futile in the space of my command,

05:40.440 --> 05:43.900
but I have two general suggestions of a certain importance.

05:44.840 --> 05:51.380
The first is to define the direction and scope of your efforts. Choose a limited period,

05:51.380 --> 05:58.960
or a limited subject, or a single author. Say to yourself, I will know something about the French

05:58.960 --> 06:08.140
Revolution, or the rise of railways, or the works of John Keats. And during a given period,

06:08.380 --> 06:15.320
to be settled beforehand, confine yourself to your choice. There is much pleasure to be derived from

06:15.320 --> 06:23.320
being a specialist. The second suggestion is to think as well as to read. I know people who read

06:23.320 --> 06:28.580
and read, and for all the good it does them they might just as well cut bread and butter.

06:29.580 --> 06:35.780
They take to reading as better men take to drink. They fly through the shires of literature on a

06:35.780 --> 06:42.300
motor-car, their sole object being motion. They will tell you how many books they have read in a

06:42.300 --> 06:48.620
year. Unless you give at least forty-five minutes to careful, fatiguing reflection,

06:49.220 --> 06:55.940
it is an awful bore at first. Upon what you are reading, your ninety minutes of a night are chiefly

06:55.940 --> 07:04.660
wasted. This means that your pace will be slow. Never mind. Forget the goal, think only of the

07:04.660 --> 07:11.460
surrounding country, and after a period, perhaps when you least expect it, you will suddenly find

07:11.460 --> 07:16.920
yourself in a lovely town on a hill. End of chapter

